item.title: Web Design
item.dc:creator: savitalakha
item.content:encoded: In this course, we will learn how to create website using HTML ,CSS and javascript.

wp:postmeta.wp:meta_value:
1) You can learn in a short period of time.
2) Limited skills.
3) You can do freelancing projects.
4) Start our own business.
5) You can earn money in a short time.
6) Work from home.
7) You can start your own training Institute.

Types of text editor: Microsoft Visual Code: Microsoft Visual Code is the latest trendy editor among developers for good reason. Free, it has all the features that a developer can expect and very good ergonomics; Atom: Atom has excellent ergonomics which greatly facilitates the handling and approach of the code for new developers. This text editor has all the functions you would expect from a good editor: built-in libraries, auto-completion of tags, etc. NotePad ++: Certainly the most well-known text editor of all time, NotePad ++ is also one of the oldest. It has passed the test of time and has been able to adapt over time by adding features regularly such as auto-completion of tags, highlighting of syntax errors in code etc. The only downside in my opinion remains its interface which is to be refined. Brackets: Brackets is a very special editor since it only focuses on front-end development languages (ie HTML, CSS and JavaScript). However, it has excellent ergonomics (UI / UX) and extensive support for supported languages. You can find instructions on the following link: http://edutechwiki.unige.ch/en/Brackets

Free, it has all the features that a developer can expect and very good ergonomics; Atom: Atom has excellent ergonomics which greatly facilitates the handling and approach of the code for new developers. This text editor has all the functions you would expect from a good editor: built-in libraries, auto-completion of tags, etc. NotePad ++: Certainly the most well-known text editor of all time, NotePad ++ is also one of the oldest. It has passed the test of time and has been able to adapt over time by adding features regularly such as auto-completion of tags, highlighting of syntax errors in code etc. The only downside in my opinion remains its interface which is to be refined. Brackets: Brackets is a very special editor since it only focuses on front-end development languages (ie HTML, CSS and JavaScript). However, it has excellent ergonomics (UI / UX) and extensive support for supported languages. You can find instructions on the following link: http://edutechwiki.unige.ch/en/Brackets

item.title: What is html?
item.dc:creator: savitalakha
item.content:encoded:
HTML is the standard markup language for creating web pages.

HTML stands for Hyper Text Markup Language

HTML describes the structure of web pages using tags

HTML elements are the building blocks of HTML pages

HTML elements are represented by tags

HTML tags label content items such as "title", "paragraph", "table", etc.

Browsers do not display HTML tags, but use them to display the content of the page.

References:https://www.w3schools.com/

item.title: Creation of first page
item.dc:creator: savitalakha
item.content:encoded:
Creation of your first HTML page.

Open any text editor such as NOTEPAD or Notepad ++

Write the HTML code below, with the tags.

Save the file with the extension .html

<!DOCTYPEhtml>
<html>
<head>
<title>Page Title</title>
</head>
<body>

<h1>This is a Heading</h1>
<p>This is a paragraph.</p>

</body>
</html>

Open the file using a browser (Firefox, Internet Explorer, Safari, Google Chrome, etc.).

Right-click on the file and choose "Open With".

PS .: The folder name and the file name must not contain spaces or special characters.

item.title: Tags
item.dc:creator: savitalakha
item.content:encoded:
General HTML page tags BODY

  • Heading:The<h1></h1>element defines a header (from 1 (the largest) to 6 (the smallest)).
  • Paragraph:The<p></p>element defines a paragraph with a line break before and after.
  • Break a line:The<br/>element breaks a line of text.
  • Pre:The text contained in a<pre></pre>element is displayed in a fixed-width font (usually Courier) and preserves spaces and line breaks.
  • Horizontal Rule:The<hr/>tag defines a thematic break in an HTML page and is most often displayed as a horizontal rule.
  • Quotation:The HTML element<q></q>defines a short quote.
  • Bi-Directional Override:The<bdo dir="rtl"></bdo>element is used to replace the meaning of the current text.
  • Comments:you can add comments to your HTML source using the following syntax:<!--write comments here-->
  • HTML Links:The<a href="http://www.good4college.com"> GOOD4College</a>element defines a page address with the name of the link.
    • The destination of the link is specified in the href attribute.
  • Image:HTML images are defined with<img src="image.jpg" alt="" width="100px" height="100px"/>.
    • The source file (src), alternative text (alt), width and height are provided as attributes:
  • Button:The<button>Click here</button>element defines a button.
  • Iframe:<iframesrc="URL"></iframe>is used to display a web page in a web page.
    • The src attribute specifies the URL (web address) of the online frame page.
  • Liste:an unordered list begins with the<ul></ul>tag.
    • List Item:each list item begins with the<li></li>tag.
  • Table:The<table></table>element defines a table structure.
    • Row: The<tr></tr>element defines a row inside the array structure.
    • Column: The<td></td>element defines a column inside the row structure.
  • Form:<form action="page.html" method="post"></form>.
    • The address where the form will be submitted (action)
    • The "way" with which the form will be submitted (method), can be post or get:
    • The input, select, textarea tags are part of the form element.
  • Input:the input tag must be written inside the form tag.This is the<input type="text"/>fill field.
    • The input tag has the following type:
    • Text:defines a line entry field.
    • Password:defines a password field with a mask.
    • Submit:Defines a button for submitting form data to a form manager.
    • Radio:defines a radio button.- The radio buttons allow the user to select ONLY ONE from a limited number of choices.
    • Checkbox:defines a check box.- Multiple choice.
    • Email:is used for the input fields which must contain an email address.
    • Hidden:allows to submit values without displaying it to the user.
  • Select:The<select></select>element defines a drop-down list:
    • The<option></option>elements define an option that can be selected if it is written between the select tags.
  • Textarea:The<textarea></textarea>element defines a multiline input field (a text area).
  • Div:The<div></div>est souvent utilis comme conteneur pour d'autres lments HTML. C'est un lment de niveau bloc.
  • Span:The<span></span>element is often used as a container for text.It's an online item.

Reference:https://www.w3schools.com/

item.title: Sample Page
item.dc:creator: savitalakha
item.content:encoded:
This is an example page. It's different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:

Hi there! I'm a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my website. I live in Los Angeles, have a great dog named Jack, and I like piña coladas. (And gettin' caught in the rain.)

...or something like this:

The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickeys to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.

As a new WordPress user, you should go to your dashboard to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!

item.title: Privacy Policy
item.dc:creator: savitalakha
item.content:encoded:
Who we are

Our website address is: http:.

What personal data we collect and why we collect it

Comments

When visitors leave comments on the site we collect the data shown in the comments form, and also the visitor’s IP address and browser user agent string to help spam detection.

An anonymized string created from your email address (also called a hash) may be provided to the Gravatar service to see if you are using it. The Gravatar service privacy policy is available here: https://automattic.com/privacy/. After approval of your comment, your profile picture is visible to the public in the context of your comment.

Media

If you upload images to the website, you should avoid uploading images with embedded location data (EXIF GPS) included. Visitors to the website can download and extract any location data from images on the website.

Contact forms

Cookies

If you leave a comment on our site you may opt-in to saving your name, email address and website in cookies. These are for your convenience so that you do not have to fill in your details again when you leave another comment. These cookies will last for one year.

If you visit our login page, we will set a temporary cookie to determine if your browser accepts cookies. This cookie contains no personal data and is discarded when you close your browser.

When you log in, we will also set up several cookies to save your login information and your screen display choices. Login cookies last for two days, and screen options cookies last for a year. If you select "Remember Me", your login will persist for two weeks. If you log out of your account, the login cookies will be removed.

If you edit or publish an article, an additional cookie will be saved in your browser. This cookie includes no personal data and simply indicates the post ID of the article you just edited. It expires after 1 day.

Embedded content from other websites

Articles on this site may include embedded content (e.g. videos, images, articles, etc.). Embedded content from other websites behaves in the exact same way as if the visitor has visited the other website.

These websites may collect data about you, use cookies, embed additional third-party tracking, and monitor your interaction with that embedded content, including tracking your interaction with the embedded content if you have an account and are logged in to that website.

Analytics

Who we share your data with

If you request a password reset, your IP address will be included in the reset email.

How long we retain your data

If you leave a comment, the comment and its metadata are retained indefinitely. This is so we can recognize and approve any follow-up comments automatically instead of holding them in a moderation queue.

For users that register on our website (if any), we also store the personal information they provide in their user profile. All users can see, edit, or delete their personal information at any time (except they cannot change their username). Website administrators can also see and edit that information.

What rights you have over your data

If you have an account on this site, or have left comments, you can request to receive an exported file of the personal data we hold about you, including any data you have provided to us. You can also request that we erase any personal data we hold about you. This does not include any data we are obliged to keep for administrative, legal, or security purposes.

Where we send your data

Visitor comments may be checked through an automated spam detection service.

Your contact information

Additional information

How we protect your data

What data breach procedures we have in place

What third parties we receive data from

What automated decision making and/or profiling we do with user data

About Us

"It is literally true that you can succeed best and quickest by helping others to succeed."

Our Story

In just 15 minutes , you can received your personalized report and begin using your Play & Learn Quiz. It is invented by us mainly  to help the students

  • Answer the questions online anywhere, anytime.
  • Use any device including your phone.
  • Play & Learn the quiz 
  • Assess Knowledge. Of course, these quizzes are meant to track, report, and evaluate learning progress and outcomes.

Meet Our Lead Instructors

"None of us, including me, ever do great things. But we can all do small things, with great love, and together we can do something wonderful."

Jack Lee

TEAM LEAD

What We're All About

"Teamwork is the ability to work together toward a common vision. The ability to direct individual accomplishments toward organizational objectives. It is the fuel that allows common people to attain uncommon results."

EXPERIENCE

Wisdom comes from experience. Experience is often a result of lack of wisdom.Practice lets us execute a task while using less and less active brain processing. It makes things automatic.

QUIZ

It assess Knowledge. Of course, eLearning quizzes are meant to track, report, and evaluate learning progress and outcomes. Also, eLearning quizzes can motivate learners to stay focused and keep moving forward.

EDUCATION

We are having some free online courses which helps you to learn & evaluate your major. Moreover, it is involves scheduling flexibility. If you believe you are unprepared , you are not alone. Several students do not feel confident . It is a best platform to overcome this problem.

"Remember, teamwork begins by building trust. And the only way to do that is to overcome our need for invulnerability."

What we learn with pleasure we never forget.

Dont just teach your children to read. Teach them to question what they read. Teach them to question everything.

Start Quiz

Online Courses

Web Design
JSON
ITE

Experience

Wisdom comes from experience. Experience is often a result of lack of wisdom.Practice lets us execute a task while using less and less activebrainprocessing. It makes things automatic.

Education

We are having some free online courses which helps you to learn & evaluate your major. Moreover, it is involves scheduling flexibility. If you believe you are unprepared , you are not alone. Several students do not feel confident . It is a best platform to overcome this problem.

Quizzes

It assess Knowledge. Of course, eLearning quizzes are meant to track, report, and evaluate learning progress and outcomes. Also, eLearning quizzes can motivate learners to stay focused and keep moving forward.

Highly Recommended by students!

"I am ron and tutor and used this for taking online quizzes from my students."

"hi! In pandemic, school are online so i find this website very useful for my childrens."

 4.5/5 Lily Granger

"Highly recommended"

 5/5 Jeson Foxx

SUCCESS STORIES

"A dream does not become reality through magic; it takes sweat, determination, andhard work." "I'm a great believer in luck, and I find the harder Iwork, the more I have of it." "Doing the best at this moment puts you in the best place for the next moment." "Hard workbeats talent if talent doesn'twork hard."

"Play & learn helps me to prepare for my exams as due to covid-19 ,i am not able to go my school ,so i find it a best way to evalute yourself." John Doe Client "Web Design course is really helpful for me." Melissa Gibson Client "i personally enjoy while taking a quiz as it is very comfortable for me to sit anywhere do the test." Alice Griffin Tracker "Of course, theses quizzes are meant to track, report, and evaluate learning progress and outcomes. " Amanda Wells Styler "As a teacher, i think that Quizzes help students identify what they know and what they don't know. The students then have a better idea of how well they are grasping the material, hopefully motivating them to study more " Ethan Little Player At the same time, quizzes can serve as a self-assessment tool which gives learners freedom to fail. Imagine you are in a classroom facing a tough but thought-provoking question. You burst to give it a try, yet face a fear of failure. But with quizzes, theres room for everyone to exert themselves, test their ideas, and go wrong. This allows learners to figure out what they do know, what they dont, what they need to focus on, and how to improve. Heather Fowler Client

item.title: Description
item.dc:creator: savitalakha
item.content:encoded:
• CSS stands for Cascading Style Sheets
  • CSS describes how HTML elements should be displayed on the screen, on paper or in another medium.
  • CSS saves a lot of work.It can control the layout of multiple web pages at the same time.
  • External style sheets are stored in CSS files.

Three ways to insert CSS

  • External style sheet
    • With an external style sheet, you can change the look of an entire website by editing just one file!
    • Each page should include a reference to the external style sheet file inside the element.The<link>element inside the<head>:

<head>
<linkrel="stylesheet"type="text/css"href="mystyle.css">
</head>

  • Internal style sheet
    • An internal style sheet can be used if a single page has a unique style.
    • Internal styles are defined in the<style>element, in the<head>section of an HTM page:

<head>
<style>
body{
background-color:linen;
}

h1{
color:maroon;
margin-left:40px;
}
</style>
</head>

  • Online Style
    • An inline style can be used to apply a unique style to a single item.
    • To use inline styles, add the style attribute to the element.The style attribute can contain any CSS property.
    • The example below shows how to change the color and the left margin of an<h1>element:

    <h1style="color:blue;margin-left:30px;">This is a heading</h1>

item.title: Description
item.dc:creator: savitalakha
item.content:encoded:
• Bootstrap is a free and open-source front-end web framework. It contains HTML and CSS-based design templates for typography, forms, buttons, navigation and other interface components, as well as optionalJavaScript extensions. Unlike many earlier web frameworks, it concerns itself with front-end development only.
  • You can download boostratp at:https://getbootstrap.com/

item.title: What is relationship between the web and the internet?
item.dc:creator: savitalakha
item.content:encoded:
• We find this term in WWW (for World Wide Web or World Web in French), it allows you to consult via a browser pages grouped on sites via the Internet. The image of the spider web is the result of hypertext links which link the pages together and which can therefore make one think of a spider web.
  • It is only an Internet application such as electronic mail (email or email in French), instant messaging, peer to peer file sharing (peer to peer in French) or file sharing via the FTP protocol.
  • By extension, it commonly (and therefore incorrectly) designates the Internet as a whole and its traces are often found in the addresses of websites also called URLs (Uniform Resource Locator).watch?v=CX_HyY3kbZw

item.title: Creation of first page
item.dc:creator: savitalakha
item.content:encoded:
Creation of your first HTML page.

Open any text editor such as NOTEPAD or Notepad ++

Write the HTML code below, with the tags.

Save the file with the extension .html

<!DOCTYPEhtml>
<html>
<head>
<title>Page Title</title>
</head>
<body>

<h1>This is a Heading</h1>
<p>This is a paragraph.</p>

</body>
</html>

Open the file using a browser (Firefox, Internet Explorer, Safari, Google Chrome, etc.).

Right-click on the file and choose "Open With".

PS .: The folder name and the file name must not contain spaces or special characters.

item.title: General HTML page tags BODY
item.dc:creator: savitalakha
item.content:encoded:
• Heading:The<h1></h1>element defines a header (from 1 (the largest) to 6 (the smallest)).
  • Paragraph:The<p></p>element defines a paragraph with a line break before and after.
  • Break a line:The<br/>element breaks a line of text.
  • Pre:The text contained in a<pre></pre>element is displayed in a fixed-width font (usually Courier) and preserves spaces and line breaks.
  • Horizontal Rule:The<hr/>tag defines a thematic break in an HTML page and is most often displayed as a horizontal rule.
  • Quotation:The HTML element<q></q>defines a short quote.
  • Bi-Directional Override:The<bdo dir="rtl"></bdo>element is used to replace the meaning of the current text.
  • Comments:you can add comments to your HTML source using the following syntax:<!--write comments here-->
  • HTML Links:The<a href="http://www.good4college.com"> GOOD4College</a>element defines a page address with the name of the link.
    • The destination of the link is specified in the href attribute.
  • Image:HTML images are defined with<img src="image.jpg" alt="" width="100px" height="100px"/>.
    • The source file (src), alternative text (alt), width and height are provided as attributes:
  • Button:The<button>Click here</button>element defines a button.
  • Iframe:<iframesrc="URL"></iframe>is used to display a web page in a web page.
    • The src attribute specifies the URL (web address) of the online frame page.
  • Liste:an unordered list begins with the<ul></ul>tag.
    • List Item:each list item begins with the<li></li>tag.
  • Table:The<table></table>element defines a table structure.
    • Row: The<tr></tr>element defines a row inside the array structure.
    • Column: The<td></td>element defines a column inside the row structure.
  • Form:<form action="page.html" method="post"></form>.
    • The address where the form will be submitted (action)
    • The "way" with which the form will be submitted (method), can be post or get:
    • The input, select, textarea tags are part of the form element.
  • Input:the input tag must be written inside the form tag.This is the<input type="text"/>fill field.
    • The input tag has the following type:
    • Text:defines a line entry field.
    • Password:defines a password field with a mask.
    • Submit:Defines a button for submitting form data to a form manager.
    • Radio:defines a radio button.- The radio buttons allow the user to select ONLY ONE from a limited number of choices.
    • Checkbox:defines a check box.- Multiple choice.
    • Email:is used for the input fields which must contain an email address.
    • Hidden:allows to submit values without displaying it to the user.
  • Select:The<select></select>element defines a drop-down list:
    • The<option></option>elements define an option that can be selected if it is written between the select tags.
  • Textarea:The<textarea></textarea>element defines a multiline input field (a text area).
  • Div:The<div></div>est souvent utilis comme conteneur pour d'autres lments HTML. C'est un lment de niveau bloc.
  • Span:The<span></span>element is often used as a container for text.It's an online item.

Reference:https://www.w3schools.com/

JSON
ITE

Frequently Asked Questions.

How many cm in half a meter?

To calculate a value in meters to the corresponding value in centimeters, just multiply the quantity in meters by100 (the conversion factor).

50 cm=0.5m

What is the smallest country in the world? Vatican CityBased on landmass,Vatican Cityis the smallest country in the world, measuring just 0.2 square miles, almost 120 times smaller than the island of Manhattan. Who was the first Saka king in India?

An Indo-Scythian king, Moga (or Maues) was the first Saka king in India who established Saka power in Gandhara and extended supremacy over north-western India.

How do you create a link that will connect to another web page when clicked?

To create hyperlinks, or links that connect to another web page, use the href tag. The general format for this is: <a href=site>text</a>
Replace site with the actual page URL that is supposed to be linked to when the text is clicked.

Why You Should Join Our quizz.

Success isn't something that just happens - success is learned, success is practiced and then it is shared.Practicedoes notmake perfect. Onlyperfect practice makes perfect. Success is nothing more than a few simple disciplines, practiced every day. Also,it prepared you for future.

item.title: HTML
item.dc:creator: savitalakha
item.content:encoded:
HTML is the standard markup language for creating web pages.
HTML stands for Hyper Text Markup Language
HTML describes the structure of web pages using tags
HTML elements are the building blocks of HTML pages
HTML elements are represented by tags
HTML tags label content items such as "title", "paragraph", "table", etc.
Browsers do not display HTML tags, but use them to display the content of the page.
